Final Exam Part 2

Final Exam Part 2 Malia Mulligan June 14th, 2023

INTRODUCTION:

For this part of the Final Exam, I chose to use the EGRET package, as opposed to the FIA package. I identified stations from the USGS Monitoring List for Washington, and I chose to focus on stations in the Okanogan River Basin. The USGS has 12 monitoring stations in the Okanogan River Basin. The EGRET package gives you the chance to statistically analyze and visualize different characteristics of Rivers, streams, and creeks. For example, water quality trends and discharge.

Set the directory, load necessary and appropriate packages and libraries.

# Explore the EGRET Package, familiarize yourself with the traditional workflow and with variable descriptions. 
vignette("EGRET")

Loading in the Data

At USGS monitoring stations, several different parameters are recorded. These parameter each have a Parameter Code and Definition, which can be find on the USGS website. For this project, I was interested in looking at the discharge parameter, which has a code of “00060,” and which recorded discharge at the station in cubic feet per second. Each of the 12 stations were loaded into my R user space as follows below (with different variable names for the different stations).

https://help.waterdata.usgs.gov/parameter_cd?group_cd=PHY

There will be warning messages saying that there were columns with NA, this will be fixed lated on in the data wrangling section of this exercise.

# Load in EGRET Data. For this project, I am focusing on stations in the Okanogan River Basin in Washington State. The station names were pulled from the USGS website at: https://waterdata.usgs.gov/wa/nwis/current/?type=flow

Regression or ANOVA

When deciding whether to run a regression or ANOVA on this data, I began with checking the assumptions of each. The variable I was most curious about understanding the factors that play into it was the discharge rate at each station (the Q variable in our Daily EGRET Object).

ANOVA can be used when the dependent variable is numerical and the independent variable is categorical. So, in the case of our discharge rate, we could test how the discharge differs at each station. For ANOVA, the assumptions we have to keep in mind include: 1) The observations in each group are normally distributed, 2) Standard deviations of each group are approximately equal 3) the observations in each group are independent.

boxplot(log(Okanagan_river_Daily$Q) ~ Okanagan_river_Daily$name)

Neither the first nor second assumptions were met, so I moved onto regression.

According to our lecture notes, regression is a statistical procedure that determines the equation for the straight line that best fits a specific set of data. Sticking with our same dependent variable, the “Q” values or discharge rate, I began regression analysis. The assumptions of regression are: 1) the relationship between X and Y is linear, 2), 3) The variance of Y at every value of X is the same (homogeneity of variances), 4) the observations are independent. I ran two linear model regressions, and one loess regression on the data, but first I plotted some relationships.

As far as linearity between the variables discharge area and discharge rate are definitely not linearly related when the extreme outliers are included. By omitting these outliers, the data does become much more linear, although still weakly.

As far as the best regression model, the first linear regression with the outlier data removed had the most diagonally linear QQ plot. Furthermore, the residual scatter plot was the most flat, although still not perfect. However, its p values were not statistically significant and its R-squared was incredibly low.

This means that, the discharge area is not a predictor or part of the regression equation for discharge rate, and that other variables need to be included in the equation. In the future, it would be interesting to consider other variables such as average precipitation and temperature and river depth.

  addCircleMarkers(data = qmean,

    position = "topright",
    html = "<h4>Okanagan River Basin USGS Stations</h4>"

Conclusion

The USGS Water monitoring stations in the Okanagan River Basin demonstrate diversity when it comes to drainage areas and drainage rates. Understanding this information is useful for flood management and response, as well as water supply.

A future study should analyze other factors that might play a role in these variables, and should also consider locations in this basin that are located in Canada. There are several factors that would be interesting to explore including elevation, precipitation, and temperature data. Some of this information could be accessed by defining other parameters in the EGRET package. Including these variables might make a future regression analyze more valuable.

It would also be interesting to translate this study to a different river basin with more stations to see if that could increase noticeable patterns.
